observations.recommendation:
a. Direct the City Treasurer to instruct the AOs to liquidate cash advances for payroll within five (5) days after each fifteen (15) or end of the month pay period as prescribed in COA Circular No. 97-002;
b. Direct the City Treasurer to coordinate with the relevant necessary offices to formulate policies and procedures that will facilitate better compliance with the liquidation of cash advances within the reglementary period;
c. Direct the City Accountant to enforce withholding of salary from the concerned city officials/personnel with unliquidated cash advances in case of failure to submit liquidation reports after demand has been made pursuant to Item 5.1.3, second paragraph of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
d. Direct the City Accountant to maintain up-to-date individual subsidiary ledger for each accountable officer to determine correct accountabilities.

a. Direct the CPDO to review the AIP in conjunction with the Local Development Investment Plan (LDIP) to ensure that all PPAs are included thereto;

b. Direct the CPDO to reevaluate the AIP to ensure that charges for the 20 percent DF be appropriately categorized as Personnel Services (PS), MOOE and Capital Outlay (CO); and

c. Direct the City Budget Officer to coordinate with the Planning and Development Coordinator in the formulation of the local development plan.

a. Direct the City Accountant and/or authorized representative together with the City Treasurer to ascertain that cash advances granted to the AOs are covered by sufficient amount of fidelity bond, in accordance with Section 5.1 of Treasury Circular No. 02-2009;

b. Direct the City Accountant to not grant additional cash advances to AOs with previous cash advances not settled and proper accounting is made; and

c. Direct the City Accountant to maintain up-to-date individual subsidiary ledgers to facilitate monitoring of cash advances of Accountable Officers.

a. Direct the City HRMO to ensure that the approval of loan application of the personnel should not result in net take home pay lower than ₱5,000.00 as required in the GAA;

b. Direct the City Accountant to evaluate the capacity to pay of the employees before recommending approval of loans; and

c. Require the City Accountant and City HRMO to enjoin all employees of the City to comply with the requirements set forth under Sec. 56 of the GAA and to adopt control measures to ensure that their net take home pay is not lower than ₱5,000.00.

a. Direct the City HRMO to ensure that all job order personnel are engaged through formal job order contracts/assignment orders, upon authorization by the Sangguniang Panlungsod, to promote transparency, accountability, and the proper use of public resources;

b. Direct the City HRMO to coordinate with all Department Heads to ensure that the accomplishment reports of job order personnel outline the specific tasks completed, measurable results achieved and commensurate to the number of working hours paid; and

c. Direct the City HRMO to keep accurate and updated records of all employees in the City preferably the JO workers to enable effective tracking and management of human resources and ensuring the efficient use of public funds.

a. Direct the City SWDO to formulate guidelines with an aim in ensuring that the City provides medical assistance to individuals in crisis situation in accordance with Section X of DSWD Memorandum Circular No. 6 series of 2023, an amendment to DSWD MC No. 16 series of 2022;

b. Direct the City SWDO to request for office equipment such as laptop to serve as a data base for all beneficiaries of the cash assistance of the City; and

c. Direct the City Accountant to ensure that all supporting documents of the liquidation reports for medical assistance are accounted for through an assigned sequential number.

a. Direct the City SWDO to include in the submission of liquidation reports the beneficiary’s application form, recent photographs and endorsed or approved list by the City Mayor of the Nonagenarians;

b. Direct the City SWDO to include in the submission of liquidation reports the endorsed or approved list by the City Mayor of the senior citizen birthday gift beneficiaries;

c. Direct the City SWDO to formulate well-defined guidelines for enforcement to maintain and update the registry of senior citizens in close coordination with the CCR and Indigency offices including the barangay and senior citizen leaders of each barangay; and

d. Direct the City Accountant to ensure the completeness of supporting documents on the liquidation report by requiring the Accountable Officers to provide all necessary documents before approving the liquidation.

a. Direct the CHMD and CHO to identify and determine the specific positions that are eligible to receive hazard pay with descriptions as to actual exposure to occupational risk/perils to life and submit to the Secretary of Health for the approval of the plantilla positions of the eligible employees and submit copy to the Audit Team for verification;

b. Direct the CSWDO to obtain certification from the DSWD Secretary or his/her duly authorized representative, or the Regional Director of DSWD Field Office, which would confirm that status of the RSW’s status as PSW and submit copy to the Audit Team for verification;

c. Direct the City Accountant to strictly grant hazard pay to personnel who are eligible to receive the allowance in accordance with Section 7 of IRR of R.A. No. 7305 and Section 10 of DSWD MC No. 5, series of 2022; and

d. Direct the City Accountant to cause the refund of the Hazard Pay granted to regular and contractual officers/employees since its implementation without prejudice to the issuance of Notice of Disallowance by the Audit Team, if warranted.

We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to direct the City Accountant to:
a) Maintain complete subsidiary ledgers for each controlling account appearing in the Trial Balance in accordance with the provisions of Section 4(e), Chapter 2 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I to ascertain details of the individual account;
b) Adapt a computerized accounting system for the City’s financial transactions to ensure greater accuracy level, efficiency in reporting, allow data storage and increase security and management.

We recommended and the City Accountant agreed to:
a) Include and record only lawful expenditures and obligations in the Accounts payable if supported with complete and appropriate documents;
b) Require all offices to submit before the year ends, all valid and unpaid obligations to suppliers and employees to be charged against the current year appropriation to facilitate inclusion in the Accounts Payable for the year;
c) Maintain subsidiary ledgers with sufficient details of Accounts Payable to support the General Ledger balance of the said account; and
d) Revert to the unappropriated surplus the Accounts Payable which remained unclaimed for more than two years or those not supported with valid obligations pursuant to Section 98 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
Direct the Inventory Committee to follow the guidelines and procedures in the inventory taking by completing all the preliminary activities before the actual physical count of all City’s PPE whether acquired through purchase or donation, including those constructed by administration and found at station pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated 
January 31, 2020;
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete all planned activities/procedures in the approved Property Inventory Plan (PIP) and prepare the RPCPPE pursuant to Item 6.2.10 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated                January 31, 2020;
Require the General Services Office (GSO) to update its property records based on the result of the physical inventory and reconcile with the accounting records to come up with the reliable balances of PPE accounts pursuant to Item 5.12 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated                    January 31, 2020; and
Instruct the GSO to initiate disposal procedures for the unlocated or non-existing PPEs following the procedures under the cited COA Circular.

We recommended that the City Mayor:
Direct the contractor to immediately rectify or correct the deficiencies to prevent further deterioration of the infrastructure projects. Otherwise, direct the contractor to pay for the uninstalled items and construction defects;
Instruct the City Engineer to ensure that the defects are corrected as soon as possible so that the projects could start operation;
Henceforth, direct the City Engineer and the Committee on Inspection and Verification to conduct actual inspection on the project completion and not merely rely on the Accomplishment Report of the contractor so that the deficiencies observed could be corrected before final payment pursuant to Item 7 of Annex E of the RIRR of RA No. 9184; and
Propose to the Sangguniang Panlungsod (SP) an ordinance for the appropriate rents and fees for the use of market stalls and suggested rates of the function rooms once the two projects are ready for business or occupancy.

We recommended and OIC-Accountant agreed to:

Enforce immediate settlement of long outstanding cash advances totaling ₱662,775.00 pursuant to COA Circular Nos. 97-02 and 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively;

Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers especially those cash advances that has been outstanding for more than one year;

Impose withholding of salary and the application of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

Require retiring accountable official or employee to undertake an authorization (in affidavit form) to deduct financial obligations including unliquidated cash advances from the terminal leave benefits pursuant to 5.1.3 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and

Assign personnel from the Accounting Office who will closely monitor the movement of all outstanding cash advances and prepare quarterly report copy furnished the Audit Team.

We recommended that the City Mayor instruct the following officials:

a.) The ECC Head and the City Administrator to strictly adhere to the provisions of Tax Ordinance No. 17-045 particularly on the use of the ECC and on the booking process;

b.)The City Legal Office prepare contract on the use of the ECC for approval of the City Mayor;

c.)The CTO strictly impose the prescribed rental rates of the aforementioned Tax Ordinance and follow the provisions on the giving of discounts; and

d.) ECC administrator to install sub meter in order to properly determine the actual electric consumption of the ECC renters and other occupants of the ECC.

